{"title_page": "Tim Sherwood", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=July 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2013}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name                 = Tim Sherwood\n| image                = Sherwood 1.jpg\n| image_size           =\n| caption              = Sherwood managing Aston Villa away to Chelsea in October 2015\n| fullname             = Timothy Alan Sherwood<ref name=\"Hugman2005-06\">{{Cite book | editor-first = Barry J. | editor-last = Hugman | title = The PFA Footballers' Who's Who 2005/2006 | year = 2005 | publisher = Queen Anne Press | isbn = 978-1-85291-662-6 | page = 371 }}</ref>\n| birth_date           = {{birth date and age|1969|2|6|df=y}}<ref name=\"Hugman2005-06\"/>\n| birth_place          = [[Borehamwood]], England<ref name=\"Hugman2005-06\"/>\n| height               = {{height|ft=6|in=1}}<ref name=\"Hugman2005-06\"/>\n| position             = [[Midfielder]]\n| currentclub          =\n| youthyears1 = {{0|0000}}\u20131987 | youthclubs1 = [[Watford F.C.|Watford]]\n| years1   = 1987\u20131989 | clubs1   = [[Watford F.C.|Watford]] | caps1   = 32 | goals1   = 2\n| years2   = 1989\u20131992 | clubs2   = [[Norwich City F.C.|Norwich City]] | caps2   = 71 | goals2   = 10\n| years3   = 1992\u20131999 | clubs3   = [[Blackburn Rovers F.C.|Blackburn Rovers]] | caps3   = 246 | goals3   = 25\n| years4   = 1999\u20132003 | clubs4   = [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham Hotspur]] | caps4   = 93 | goals4   = 12\n| years5   = 2003\u20132004 | clubs5   = [[Portsmouth F.C.|Portsmouth]] | caps5   = 30 | goals5   = 1\n| years6   = 2004\u20132005 | clubs6   = [[Coventry City F.C.|Coventry City]] | caps6   = 11 | goals6   = 0\n| totalcaps = 483\n| totalgoals = 50\n| nationalyears1   = 1990 | nationalteam1   = [[England national under-21 football team|England U21]] | nationalcaps1   = 4 | nationalgoals1   = 0\n| nationalyears2   = 1994 | nationalteam2   = [[England B national football team|England B]] | nationalcaps2   = 1 | nationalgoals2   = 0\n| nationalyears3   = 1999 | nationalteam3   = [[England national football team|England]] | nationalcaps3   = 3 | nationalgoals3   = 0\n| manageryears1   = 2013\u20132014\n| managerclubs1   = [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham Hotspur]]\n| manageryears2   = 2015\n| managerclubs2   = [[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa]]\n}}\n'''Timothy Alan Sherwood''' (born 6 February 1969) is an English professional [[Association football|football]] [[manager (association football)|manager]] and former [[midfielder]].\n\nAs a player, he was a midfielder from 1987 until 2005, notably as captain of [[Blackburn Rovers F.C.|Blackburn Rovers]]' [[Premier League]] title-winning side in 1995. He also played for [[Watford F.C.|Watford]], [[Norwich City F.C.|Norwich City]], [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham Hotspur]], [[Portsmouth F.C.|Portsmouth]] and [[Coventry City F.C.|Coventry City]]. He made three appearances for the [[England national football team|England national team]] in 1999.\n\nSherwood began his coaching career at Tottenham Hotspur, progressing from assistant first team coach to manager in a five-year spell, then managing the club from December 2013 to his dismissal in May 2014. He resumed his managerial career at [[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa]] in February 2015, taking them to that season's [[FA Cup]] [[2015 FA Cup Final|final]] and saving them from relegation from the [[Premier League]], until being sacked in October 2015. Sherwood was director of football at [[Swindon Town F.C.|Swindon Town]] from November 2016 until June 2017.\n\n==Club career==\n\n===Early career===\nBorn in [[Borehamwood]], [[Hertfordshire]],<ref name=\"Hugman2005-06\"/> Sherwood supported [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] as a child.<ref name=\"mirror\">{{ cite web|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/sport/football/news/video-tottenham-caretaker-manager-tim-2952177 |title=Tottenham caretaker manager Tim Sherwood admits he is an ARSENAL fan |date=22 December 2013 |publisher=mirror.co.uk }}</ref> He made his debut for [[Watford F.C.|Watford]] against [[Sheffield Wednesday]] on 12 September 1987. He made a total of 32 league appearances in Division Two for Watford before moving to [[Norwich City F.C.|Norwich City]] in July 1989. He played 88 games scoring 13 goals for Norwich before joining [[Blackburn Rovers F.C.|Blackburn Rovers]] in February 1992.<ref name=\"canaries\">{{ cite web|url=http://www.ex-canaries.co.uk/players/sherwood.htm |title=Flown From the Nest \u2013 Tim Sherwood |date=22 May 2007 |publisher=ex-canaries.co.uk }}</ref>\n\n===Blackburn Rovers===\nAs one of [[Kenny Dalglish]]'s first signings for Blackburn, he initially struggled to make the first team but went on to become a core player. Under his captaincy, Blackburn finished second in the Premiership in [[1993-94 in English football|1993\u201394]] before winning it the following season. During his time at the club Dalglish wanted to sign both [[Zinedine Zidane]] and [[Christophe Dugarry]], who were playing in France for [[FC Girondins de Bordeaux|Bordeaux]], but Rovers owner [[Jack Walker]] reportedly said to Dalglish: \"Why do you want to sign Zidane when we have Tim Sherwood?\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.blackburn.vitalfootball.co.uk/article.asp?a=47576 |title=The Ones That Got Away&nbsp;... Zidane |date=18 January 2007 |publisher=blackburn.vitalfootball.co.uk }}</ref>\n\n===Tottenham Hotspur===\nWith Sherwood unsettled in 1999 and having family and business links in [[Hertfordshire]], [[George Graham (footballer)|George Graham]] paid a reported fee of \u00a33 million to bring him to Tottenham Hotspur in the first week of February 1999. He made his debut for Spurs as an 87th-minute substitute for [[Mauricio Taricco]] in the 0\u20130 draw with Coventry on 6 February. He was cup-tied for their victory in the [[1999 Football League Cup Final]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football-nielsen-header-caps-drama-1082209.html|title=Football: Nielsen header caps drama |publisher=Independent |date=22 March 1999 |accessdate=8 February 2017}}</ref> Sherwood won a runners-up medal with Spurs in the [[Football League Cup Final 2002|2002 League Cup Final]], when they were beaten by his former club Blackburn.<ref>{{cite news|title=Cole strike stuns Spurs|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/worthington_cup/1834988.stm|accessdate=20 April 2015|work=BBC Sport|date=24 February 2002}}</ref>\n\n===Portsmouth===\nIn January 2003, Sherwood informed the press that he had had a major argument with Spurs manager [[Glenn Hoddle]] and that Hoddle had told him that he would never play for the club again.{{citation needed|date=December 2013}} He left Tottenham, moving to Portsmouth on an initial four-month contract on 29 January. Upon signing he immediately became a regular in the side that went on to win the [[Football League Championship|First Division Championship]] that season, scoring once in the process, in a 5\u20130 win away to [[Millwall F.C.|Millwall]] on 1 March.<ref>{{cite web\n|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_div_1/2789903.stm\n|title=Millwall 0\u20135 Portsmouth\n|publisher=[[BBC]]\n|date=1 March 2003 |accessdate=6 November 2009}}</ref> Sherwood remained an important member of the Pompey squad for the first half of the [[2003\u201304 Premier League]] season, scoring a brace in a 5\u20132 win against Third Division [[Northampton Town]] in the League Cup second round on 23 September.<ref>{{cite web\n|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/league_cup/3125194.stm\n|title=Portsmouth 5\u20132 Northampton\n|publisher=[[BBC]]\n|date=23 September 2003 |accessdate=6 November 2009}}</ref> He broke his leg against Tottenham on 26 December, after a challenge by his former teammate Taricco.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Marshall|first1=Adam|title=Sherwood injury agony|url=http://www1.skysports.com/football/news/11674/2284303/sherwood-injury-agony|accessdate=20 April 2015|work=Sky Sports}}</ref> It was to be his last match for the club as, along with fellow veteran [[Teddy Sheringham]], he was released in the 2004 close season.\n\n===Coventry City===\nOn 9 July 2004, Sherwood signed for [[Peter Reid]]'s [[Coventry City F.C.|Coventry City]] on a two-year deal with Coventry and said that he would \"desperately like to achieve promotion\" with the club.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/c/coventry_city/3879889.stm |title=Sherwood Signs for Coventry |date=9 July 2004 |publisher=[[BBC Sport]]}}</ref> Although he was the captain, he was unpopular with fans, due to his frequent injuries, high wages and decision to do television punditry during his spell.<ref>{{cite news|last1=McCartney|first1=Aidan|title=Looking back: Tim Sherwood's disastrous spell with Sky Blues|url=http://www.coventrytelegraph.net/sport/football/transfer-news/looking-back-tim-sherwoods-disastrous-7114171|accessdate=20 April 2015|work=[[Coventry Telegraph]]|date=13 May 2014}}</ref> At the end of the 2004\u201305 season, Coventry had not been promoted and the club announced that Sherwood could leave on a free transfer. He parted company with the Sky Blues by mutual consent on 1 July 2005.\n\n==International career==\nDuring his time with Blackburn Rovers he added an [[England B national football team|England B]] cap to the [[England national under-21 football team|England Under 21]] honours he picked up whilst at Norwich.\n\nAt the age of 30, Sherwood made his debut for [[England national football team|England]] in their 3\u20131 [[UEFA Euro 2000 qualification]] victory over [[Poland national football team|Poland]] at [[Wembley Stadium (1923)|Wembley]] on 27 March 1999, under new manager [[Kevin Keegan]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/sport/football/305631.stm|title=Scholes gives Keegan winning start|date=28 March 1999|accessdate=18 March 2014|work=BBC}}</ref> He earned a further two caps that year: in a 1\u20131 friendly draw with [[Hungary national football team|Hungary]] in Budapest on 28 April, and a goalless qualifying draw with [[Sweden national football team|Sweden]] at Wembley on 5 June.<ref>{{cite news|title=Sport: Football  Scholes off as English hopes crumble|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/sport/football/361778.stm|accessdate=20 April 2015|work=BBC Sport|date=5 June 1999}}</ref>\n\n==Managerial career==\n\n===Tottenham Hotspur===\nIn October 2008, Sherwood joined [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham Hotspur]] as assistant first team coach, under new manager Harry Redknapp.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/t/tottenham_hotspur/7694285.stm |title=Redknapp adds Sherwood to staff |publisher=[[BBC Sport]] |date=31 October 2008 }}</ref> Sherwood became Technical Director in 2012 and in that role led Spurs' Under-21 side in the inaugural [[2012\u201313 Professional U21 Development League|Under-21 Premier League season]], guiding the side to finish top in both group and elite stages. Sherwood's side eventually lost the league final 3\u20132 to Manchester United.<ref>{{cite web|title=Tim Sherwood, Manager Profile|url=http://www.premierleague.com/en-gb/clubs/managers/profile.overview.html/tim-sherwood|website=Premier League|accessdate=15 February 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Roy Keane ready to hold talks over joining Blackburn Rovers|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/football-league/roy-keane-ready-to-hold-talks-over-joining-blackburn-rovers-8194671.html|website=The Independent|accessdate=15 February 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn 16 December 2013, Tottenham announced that Sherwood would \"assume first team coaching duties\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Tim Sherwood assumes First Team coaching duties|url=http://www.tottenhamhotspur.com/news/club-announcement-%C2%AD-tim-sherwood-assumes-first-team-coaching-duties-161213/}}</ref> following the departure of [[Andr\u00e9 Villas-Boas]] as the manager. He lost his first game in charge, 2\u20131 at home to West Ham in the fifth round of the [[2013\u201314 Football League Cup|Capital One Cup]],<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/25328568 |title=Tottenham 1\u20132 West Ham |publisher=[[BBC Sport]] |date=18 December 2013 }}</ref> but four days later managed a 3\u20132 [[Premier League]] win over Southampton.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/25387088 |title=Southampton 2\u20133 Tottenham |publisher=[[BBC Sport]] |date=22 December 2013 }}</ref> On 23 December, Spurs named Sherwood as their new head coach, handing him an 18-month contract until the end of the 2014\u201315 season.<ref>{{cite web|title=Sherwood Appointed|url=http://www.tottenhamhotspur.com/news/tim-sherwood-appointed-head-coach-231213/}}</ref> His last match as Spurs manager was a 3\u20130 win over [[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa]] on 11 May 2014. With this win Sherwood achieved a sixth-place finish in the league with Spurs with a total of 69 league points.<ref>{{cite news|title=Tottenham Hotspur 3\u20130 Aston Villa|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/27273512|accessdate=11 May 2014|work=[[BBC Sport]]|date=11 May 2014}}</ref> Sherwood was sacked by chairman [[Daniel Levy (businessman)|Daniel Levy]] on 13 May 2014.<ref>{{cite news |title=Tim Sherwood sacked as Tottenham manager |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/0/football/27389072 |work=BBC Sport |date=13 May 2014 |accessdate=22 August 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Aston Villa===\n[[File:Sherwood v Chelsea.jpg|thumbnail|Sherwood managing Aston Villa in 2015]]\nOn 14 February 2015, Sherwood was appointed as the new manager of [[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa]]. The announcement was made via the club's official [[Twitter]] page, following the sacking of [[Paul Lambert]] on 11 February.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/31470606 |title=Tim Sherwood appointed new Aston Villa boss |publisher=BBC Sport |date=14 February 2015 }}</ref> Although he attended the following day's 2\u20131 win over [[Leicester City F.C.|Leicester City]] in the [[FA Cup]] and gave a half-time team-talk, his first game in official control of the team was at home to [[Stoke City F.C.|Stoke City]] almost a week later. Villa lost the game 2\u20131 after a 93rd-minute penalty from [[Victor Moses]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/31423131 |title=Aston Villa 2\u20131 Leicester City |publisher=BBC Sport |date=15 February 2015 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/31466727 |title=Aston Villa 1\u20132 Stoke City |publisher=BBC Sport |date=21 February 2015 |accessdate=10 March 2015 }}</ref> After also losing his second game in charge, this time going down 1\u20130 to [[Newcastle United F.C.|Newcastle United]], Sherwood's first win came on 3 March 2015 against [[West Midlands (county)|West Midlands]] rivals [[West Bromwich Albion F.C.|West Bromwich Albion]]. The game finished 2\u20131, with [[Christian Benteke]] scoring a last-minute penalty, which shadowed the decision that went against Villa in the Stoke game.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/31562897 |title=Newcastle United 1\u20130 Aston Villa |publisher=BBC Sport |date=28 February 2015 |accessdate=10 March 2015 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/31598202 |title=Aston Villa 2\u20131 West Bromwich Albion |publisher=BBC Sport |date=3 March 2015 |accessdate=10 March 2015 }}</ref> Sherwood led Villa to Wembley for the first time since 2010 just four days later, after winning 2\u20130 in the [[2014-15 FA Cup#Sixth Round Proper|FA cup quarter-final]] again against West Bromwich Albion.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/31669806 |title=Aston Villa 2\u20130 West Bromwich Albion |publisher=BBC Sport |date=7 March 2015 |accessdate=10 March 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/31787629 |title=FA Cup pitch invasion: FA contacts Aston Villa & West Brom |publisher=BBC Sport |accessdate=10 March 2015}}</ref> Sherwood then led Villa to a third straight win, a 4\u20130 away win over relegation rivals [[Sunderland A.F.C.|Sunderland]] in which all goals were scored in the first half.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/31776485 |title=Sunderland 0\u20134 Aston Villa |publisher=BBC Sport |date=14 March 2015}}</ref> On 19 April 2015, Aston Villa reached the [[2015 FA Cup Final|FA Cup Final]] for the first time since [[2000 FA Cup Final|2000]], coming from behind to defeat Liverpool 2\u20131 in their semi-final at [[Wembley Stadium|Wembley]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Aston Villa 2\u20131 Liverpool|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/32273487|accessdate=20 April 2015|work=BBC Sport|date=19 April 2015}}</ref> However, they went on to lose the final 4\u20130 to Arsenal.<ref name=fafinal>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/32856754 |title=Arsenal 4\u20130 Aston Villa |work=BBC Sport |date=30 May 2015 }}</ref> After losing six consecutive matches, including a 10-game win-less run which left the team 19th in the table, Sherwood was sacked on 25 October 2015.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/34631549|title=Tim Sherwood: Aston Villa manager sacked after eight months|publisher=BBC Sport|date=25 October 2015|accessdate=25 October 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Swindon Town===\n\nOn 10 November 2016, Sherwood was appointed director of football at [[EFL League One|League One]] side [[Swindon Town F.C.|Swindon Town]].<ref>https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/37938448</ref> On 14 June 2017, it was confirmed that Sherwood would leave his post, following the club's relegation to [[EFL League Two|League Two]].<ref>https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/40278524</ref>\n\n==Media work==\nSherwood has often appeared as footballing pundit on [[Al-Jazeera Sport]] offering comments on [[English football]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thenational.ae/sport/football/teenager-tom-carroll-growing-in-stature-at-spurs|title=Teenager Tom Carroll growing in stature at Spurs |publisher=The National |date=29 September 2011}}</ref> He was also a pundit for [[Setanta Sports]] for their [[Premier League]] coverage.{{citation needed|date=October 2019}} Most recently, Sherwood has worked as a pundit on [[Prime Video]]'s Premier League Goals Show.\n\n==Honours==\n===Player===\n'''Blackburn Rovers'''\n*[[Premier League]]: [[1994\u201395 FA Premier League|1994\u201395]]<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.premierleague.com/players/78/Tim-Sherwood/overview |title=Tim Sherwood: Overview |publisher=Premier League |accessdate=18 April 2018}}</ref>\n\n'''Portsmouth'''\n*[[Football League First Division]]: [[2002\u201303 Football League First Division|2002\u201303]]\n\n'''Individual'''\n*[[PFA Team of the Year]]: [[PFA Team of the Year (1990s)#FA Premier League 3|1994\u201395 Premier League]]\n\n===Manager===\n'''Aston Villa'''\n*[[FA Cup]] runner-up: [[2015 FA Cup Final|2014\u201315]]<ref name=fafinal/>\n\n==Career statistics==\n===Club===\n:Source: {{ENFA}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|+ Appearances and goals by club, season and competition\n|-\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Club\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Season\n!colspan=\"3\"|League\n!colspan=\"2\"|[[FA Cup]]\n!colspan=\"2\"|[[EFL Cup|League Cup]]\n!colspan=\"2\"|Europe\n!colspan=\"2\"|Other\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n|-\n!Division!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals\n|-\n|rowspan=\"3\"|[[Watford F.C.|Watford]]\n|[[1987\u201388 Watford F.C. season|1987\u201388]]\n|[[Football League First Division|First Division]]\n|13||0||3||0||3||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||1{{efn|name=FMC|Appearance(s) in [[Full Members' Cup]]}}||0||20||0\n|-\n|[[1988\u201389 Watford F.C. season|1988\u201389]]\n|[[Football League Second Division|Second Division]]\n|19||2||6||0||2||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||4{{efn|name=FMC}}||0||32||2\n|-\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n!32!!2!!9!!0!!5!!0!!colspan=\"2\"|\u2014!!5!!0!!51!!2\n|-\n|rowspan=\"4\"|[[Norwich City F.C.|Norwich City]] \n|[[1989\u201390 Norwich City F.C. season|1989\u201390]]\n|First Division\n|27||3|